Raw dev notes -- Deep Dive into RAG Evaluation: Faithfulness, Metrics, and the Gemara

**Project Background:**
This project, `gemara-page-rag-experiment`, is all about trying to build a really good Retrieval Augmented Generation (RAG) system for Gemara texts. The goal is to make an AI that can answer questions about these complex religious texts accurately and, crucially, *faithfully* to the source material. It's a deep dive into how to make LLMs reliable for highly specific, nuanced domains.

**What was done in this period:**
Man, this past couple of weeks has been a whirlwind of metrics, docs, and trying to get a handle on what "good" even means in RAG.

We kicked off with some solid wins, like the `v10_kg2rag` update. Integrating Sefaria links into our knowledge graph was a huge step, giving us an `L5` quality bump of over 18 percentage points. That felt good, like we were really making progress on the core RAG retrieval.

Then it was all about refining the text processing. We got `marker tagging` to 100% using a hybrid regex+LLM approach, which was pretty neat. This helps us chunk the text more intelligently. We ran a `v10 full-539 sweep` and hit an `L5` of 0.802, which was a new high. We even tried adding a `halakhic_methodology layer`, but `v13_marker_aware` turned out to be a `NEGATIVE` experiment – sometimes you just gotta try things to know they don't work.

A big breakthrough came with `v15 prompt` engineering, pushing `L5` up to 0.860. But honestly, the real work wasn't just chasing that number. It was building out the `eval-infra hardening`. I spent a ton of time on documentation: `eval-system explainer`, `Ragas comparison`, `Ragas internals + honest blind-spot analysis`. I even built a `dashboard` with an `L5 headline chart` and `auto-refresh` so I could actually *see* what was happening.

The biggest shift was moving beyond just `L5` and really digging into `faithfulness` and `groundedness`. We implemented `R1 groundedness/faithfulness eval (L6)` and a `batch pipeline` for it. This was huge. We also added `R5 context-precision metric`. To make sure our evaluations were solid, I set up `R4 part A — judge calibration` with `blind human-review CSVs` and confirmed our human judges were reliable.

The results from `R1 faithfulness` were a bit of a gut punch – `concern confirmed`. Our initial `faith` score was around 0.49, and after a full `E1` run over 503 questions, it was 0.46. That's... not great. It really highlighted that high `L5` doesn't automatically mean the answers are *true* to the source.

We also did some `KG2RAG context-organization` and started experimenting with `R10 self-labeling prompt (v17)` to tag claims as source-based or general knowledge. And a crucial `fix` for `deterministic metadata-key batch correlation` across scripts – gotta keep that eval consistent!

**What was hard or surprising:**
The most surprising thing was how much effort went into *evaluating* the RAG system, rather than just building it. I thought I had a good handle on things with `L5` looking strong, but then `R1 faithfulness` came along and slapped me with reality. It was a stark reminder that a high-quality *answer* doesn't mean a high-quality *process* if the answer isn't grounded.

The `v13_marker_aware (NEGATIVE)` result was a minor bummer, but it's part of the process. More challenging was wrestling with the `eval-infra hardening` and making sure all the metrics were robust and reproducible. Comparing our custom eval system to Ragas was also a journey – understanding its strengths and weaknesses, and where our blind spots might be.

There was also a specific `B1` issue related to Mishnah text that we initially thought might be a problem, but after empirical testing, it turned out to be `low-harm` and a `won't-fix`. It's always tricky deciding when to chase down a rabbit hole and when to accept a minor imperfection.

**Personal Reflection:**
This period felt like a real growth spurt in my understanding of RAG. I started out focused on getting good answers (high `L5`), but I've pivoted hard into understanding *why* those answers are good, and more importantly, *if they're true*. The "concern confirmed" moment with faithfulness was a wake-up call. It's easy to get caught up in the numbers, but if the system isn't faithful, it's fundamentally broken for this kind of domain.

It's been a humbling experience, realizing how much more there is to learn about robust evaluation. I feel like I've leveled up my critical thinking about LLM outputs. It's not just about making it *sound* right, but making sure it *is* right, and that it can *prove* it's right. The extensive documentation work, especially the `SYSTEM_DIGEST` and `RESEARCH_DIGEST`, has been my way of solidifying this understanding, not just for others, but for myself. It's like I'm building a mental model of the entire RAG landscape, piece by piece.

**What's next:**
Time to tackle that faithfulness score head-on with the `master action plan`.
